I don't usually post pictures of myself from back in the day but here's one of me in New York vs. now. My recent trip to Vegas taught me that I can live freely and be seen by society as my authentic self. Just because most people where I live have known me pre-transition doesn't mean that should focus on them to make them comfortable. I need to be comfortable and happy. I don't have time to focus on people who hate, I am too busy focusing on the people who love me. I appreciate all of you that reach out to me. It means so much and that is the very reason I will never stop the fight for my LGBTQA+ brothers, sisters and non binary fam. We are valid. .

"body positivity" isn't about posting a photo on instagram where u are feeling confident or scared or are seeking some sort of validation from people around you / people you've never met. body positivity is accepting ur bod even when u feel too fat or too skinny or worthless or whatever. it's saying "yeah i'm a bit lumpy" "yeah i'm bony" "yeah i have stretch marks" and loving it bc ur bod is great and u are great and u deserve love from everyone including urself, which is something i'm getting the hang of i think. anyway, here is me, looking toned n shit in the first pic, and then a back-to-reality pic afterwards so i don't get carried away. remember that what u see on insta is not the reality of someone's entire existence - it is only the parts that they want you to see. pls remember that even peeps with bods u think are "flawless" could have insecurities too - don't mute them !! they are valid af just as u are !!!! also pls kindly remember that body dysmorphia can affect anyone. (also body hair and PROUD FAM) xxx (should i do more essays like this it is fun)
